===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|hamme|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|hamm||inner or hind part of the knee, ham|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|hamō|lang=gem-pro}}, {{recons|hammō|lang=gem-pro}}, {{recons|hanmō|lang=gem-pro}} , from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|kanam-|lang=ine-pro}}, {{recons|knāmā||thigh, shin|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with Dutch {{term|ham||ham|lang=nl}}, dialectal German {{term|Hamme||hind part of the knee, ham|lang=de}}, dialectal {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|ham||the hind part of the knee|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|höm||the ham or haunch of a horse|lang=is}}, {{etyl|mga|-}} {{term|cnáim||bone|lang=mga}}, {{etyl|grc|-}} {{term|||tr=knḗmé|shinbone|lang=grc}}. Compare {{term|gammon|lang=en}}.

